Exploratory analysis: New Henri meeting typology

New typology

This new typology has 4 categories with a minimum of 4 items per category (which is good). We’ll use shorter labels for the data analysis below. In the tables below, the items are grouped under the column called “henriLab”, and the following labels are used for the four groups:

  • Core = Core functions of the state
  • Fundamentals = State fundamental elements
  • Organisation = State organisation
  • Protection = Protection of Individuals

One can quibble about the specific label used above, but this is not an analytical issue. More importantly, the items seem to group quite naturally. I have a minor point regarding the “Protection of Individuals” category (see section at the end), but this does not make much of a difference to the end result.

Analysis of Protection of individual (without Pardons/Amnesties)

The three items below seem more consistent with a more conventional understanding of the concept of protection of individuals, I’m not sure how the inclusion of the Pardons/Amnesties item fits in this dimension.

The question to pose is: whether a country that prohibits referencums on Pardons/Amenesties is protecting individuals. To me such prohibitions are more about protecting the discretion of the state to act rather than protecting indviduals/minorities.

However, for the actual analysis it doesn’t make much difference to the scores whether we use a 3 or a 4 item version of the concept. It’s more of a conceptual issue.

Protection of individuals (3 items)

Item henriLab Question

58 Protections Are referendums on naturalisation issues prohibited?
59 Protections Are referendums on minorities or minority rights prohibited?

Annex

Substantive prohibitions that don’t occur per instrument

Below we identify the items/questions that did not elicit a prohobition. That is, we do not empirically find prohibitions for those items in the instruments listed. Not surprisingly, it is the Law-initiated referendum where certain items/questions do not get “Yes” answers (i.e., prohibitions). I guess this raises the question of how relevant it is to focus on substantive prohibitions in the case of the Law-initiated referendum.

Similarly, the Subnational referendum generates non-prohibitions but this is the result of the low number of country cases (5) which provide for this instrument.
